# AGENTS.md — example for a project adopting agent-squad

This file shows how a real project composes roles from agent-squad's three
personas plus domain skills plus file lanes. The example below is the
`dicom-store-v2` project mapped onto the construct.

Replace this content with your own role mapping when you adopt agent-squad.

> **See also:** [`examples/roles/`](roles/) — single-role fragment
> templates for the common cases (lead, cloud-architect, backend-dev,
> frontend-dev, devops-engineer). Faster starting point than copying
> this whole file when you only need a couple of roles.

---

## Role mapping

```yaml
construct_version: ">=0.1.0"

roles:

  # Lead — orchestration, briefing, PR review
  - name: lead
    alias: Pradhan
    persona: lead
    skills: []
    lanes:
      write: [docs/adr/, AGENTS.md, .ai-dlc.yml, ProjectPlan.md]
      read:  []   # default = everything

  # Architects — design before implementation, refine until Lead signs off

  - name: cloud-architect
    alias: Sanyojak (architect mode)
    persona: architect
    skills: [aws]
    lanes:
      write:
        - docs/architecture/cloud/
        - docs/adr/
        - docs/contracts/cloud-*.md
        - docs/contracts/cloud-*.yaml
      read: [docs/contracts/, infra/]

  - name: db-architect
    alias: Dharak (architect mode)
    persona: architect
    skills: [postgres]
    lanes:
      write:
        - docs/architecture/db/
        - docs/adr/
        - docs/contracts/db-*.md
        - docs/contracts/db-*.sql
      read: [app/models/, alembic/, docs/contracts/]

  # Implementers — work in parallel after contract is locked

  - name: backend-dev
    alias: Mula-lekhaka
    persona: implementer
    skills: [python, fastapi, postgres]
    lanes:
      write: [app/api/, app/services/, app/tasks/, app/schemas/, tests/]
      read:  [docs/contracts/, docs/architecture/]

  - name: frontend-dev
    alias: Drshya-shilpi
    persona: implementer
    skills: [react, ohif]
    lanes:
      write: [frontend/, public/]
      read:  [docs/contracts/, docs/architecture/]

  - name: db-engineer
    alias: Dharak (build mode)
    persona: implementer
    skills: [postgres, alembic]
    lanes:
      write: [app/models/, alembic/, alembic.ini]
      read:  [docs/contracts/, docs/architecture/db/]

  - name: devops-engineer
    alias: Sanyojak (build mode)
    persona: implementer
    skills: [docker, aws-cdk, github-actions]
    lanes:
      write: [Dockerfile*, docker-compose*, cdk/, .github/workflows/, .env.example]
      read:  [docs/architecture/cloud/, docs/contracts/]

contract_first:
  required_for:
    - feature_kind: api
      contract_path: docs/contracts/api-*.ts
    - feature_kind: schema
      contract_path: docs/contracts/db-*.md
    - feature_kind: event
      contract_path: docs/contracts/event-*.yaml
    - feature_kind: iac
      contract_path: docs/contracts/cloud-*.yaml
```

---

## Project-specific overrides

Beyond the role mapping, a project may add rules that layer on top of the
construct. These are **project-owned** — agent-squad doesn't know about them,
but `finish-feature` honours them via `pre-pr` hook handlers declared by
project-specific skills.

### Multi-tenancy review

Every backend-dev PR must include a "multi-tenant query check" line in the
self-review section. The check verifies every new query filters by `tenant_id`.
Implemented as a project hook in `scripts/multi-tenant-check.py`, registered
under `.ai-dlc.yml` `hooks.custom`.

### DevOps approval gate

PRs touching `.github/workflows/` require an explicit Lead approval comment
before merge. Implemented as a project rule, enforced by Lead at the review
stage (no separate hook).

---

## Notes

- The same person may play multiple roles depending on the issue. Sanyojak
  plays `cloud-architect` for design tickets and `devops-engineer` for build
  tickets. The role is a function of the work, not the person.
- The Sanskrit aliases are cosmetic. The construct routes by `persona` and
  `name`, never by `alias`.
- This example deliberately uses both `architect` and `implementer` for DB
  and infra work, showing how design vs build naturally split.
